[159.335421, "i", "cat << 'EOF' > /output/audit_findings.txt\nAUDIT FINDINGS REPORT: EVALUATION OF FRAUD DETECTION MODEL\nDate: May 27, 2026\nAuditor: Lead AI & Financial Analyst\n\nWe have performed a comprehensive audit of the draft model performance evaluation prepared by the junior analyst. Our review identified several critical analytical errors, misleading claims, and missing operational checks. This report details our findings, explains why they matter, and corrects the metrics.\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\nFINDING 1: Inclusion of Automated Test / QA Data (Batch 99) in Performance Metrics\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n- Claim in Draft: \"The XGBoost fraud detection model was evaluated against 5,650 held-out transactions... Accuracy: 88.3%, AUC-ROC: 0.9182.\"\n- Correction & Fact: The raw predictions export contains 150 records from Batch 99 (TransactionID prefix '9000') with an artificial ~50% fraud rate (73 positive, 77 negative) where the model achieved exactly 100% accuracy and an AUC-ROC of 1.0000. \n- Why it matters: Batch 99 represents QA integration testing or synthetic scripts with a deterministic structure, not real production transactions. Including this batch heavily inflates the reported AUC-ROC from 0.8861 (clean data) to 0.9182. This gives the false impression that the model is significantly more accurate at distinguishing fraud than it actually is, leading to overconfidence in production performance.\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\nFINDING 2: Inclusion of Out-of-Period Data\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n- Claim in Draft: \"Scoring period: January 15 - April 30, 2026\" (implied in the methodology as using all 5,650 rows).\n- Correction & Fact: The dataset contains 585 records with a 'scored_at' date after April 30, 2026 (ranging from May 1 to May 11). This includes 500 real transactions (prefix '300x') and 85 QA transactions (Batch 99). These records fall completely outside the specified quarterly holdout window.\n- Why it matters: To maintain rigorous quarterly business reviews, evaluation windows must be strictly bounded. The inclusion of post-period records represents a pipeline export error that distorts the actual quarterly statistics and violates the defined scope.\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\nFINDING 3: Mathematical & Logical Blunder on Performance Targets\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n- Claim in Draft: \"Based on the strong AUC of 0.9182 and accuracy of 88.3%, this model meets our performance targets... Targets (AUC > 0.80, Accuracy > 95%)\"\n- Correction & Fact: The analyst claimed the model met all performance targets, but the model's reported accuracy of 88.3% is far below the stated deployment target of 95%.\n- Why it matters: This is an egregious logical error in a business-critical deployment document. It demonstrates a lack of basic verification that could have easily been flagged during a superficial review.\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\nFINDING 4: Inappropriate Use of Accuracy for Highly Imbalanced Fraud Data\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n- Claim in Draft: Using \"Accuracy: 88.3%\" and a target of \"Accuracy > 95%\" as primary evaluation metrics.\n- Correction & Fact: In a realistic fraud dataset where the clean fraud prevalence is only 3.24% (162 out of 5,000), a naive baseline model that classifies all transactions as non-fraud (predicts 0 for everything) would achieve an accuracy of 96.76%. This naive model easily beats the 95% accuracy target but catches $0 in fraud and is completely useless.\n- Why it matters: Evaluating a fraud model on overall accuracy is highly misleading. It penalizes model alerts (which create false positives but are necessary to catch true fraud). The team must instead prioritize AUC-ROC, Pre"]
[159.343537, "i", "cision, Recall, and F-1 Score to assess discriminative power and operational efficiency.\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\nFINDING 5: Complete Neglect of Operational Capacity and Financial Impact\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n- Claim in Draft: \"Applied threshold of 0.5... is recommended for production deployment. No further tuning is required.\"\n- Correction & Fact: The draft completely ignores the operational capacity of the fraud review team (1,500 alerts/day) and the financial consequences of the chosen threshold. At the 0.5 threshold, the clean model would generate 667 alerts over 5,000 transactions. Projected to the quarterly volume of 2,800,000, this creates 373,520 alerts, or ~4,150 alerts per day (using 90 days per quarter). This is 2.7x higher than the team's capacity of 1,500 alerts/day, which would completely overwhelm operations and cause thousands of alerts to go unreviewed, leaking millions in fraud.\n- Why it matters: Models cannot be deployed in a vacuum. A threshold of 0.5 is operationally infeasible and financially suboptimal. The threshold must be tuned specifically to align with review capacity and minimize total quarterly business cost.\nEOF\n"]
[159.348348, "o", "cat << 'EOF' > /output/audit_findings.txt\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> AUDIT FINDINGS REPORT: EVALUATION OF FRAUD DETECTION MODEL\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> Date: May 27, 2026\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r---------\u001b[?2004h> Auditor: Lead AI & Financial Analyst\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> \r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> We have performed a comprehensive audit of the draft model performance evaluation prepared by the junior analyst. Our review identified several critical analytical errors, misleading claims, and missing operational checks. This report details our findings, explains why they matter, and corrects the metrics.\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> \r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> --------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> FINDING 1: Inclusion of Automated Test / QA Data (Batch 99) in Performance Metrics\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> --------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r,000 transactions. Pro\u001b[?2004h> - Claim in Draft: \"The XGBoost fraud detection model was evaluated against 5,650 held-out transactions... Accuracy: 88.3%, AUC-ROC: 0.9182.\"\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> - Correction & Fact: The raw predictions export contains 150 records from Batch 99 (TransactionID prefix '9000') with an artificial ~50% fraud rate (73 positive, 77 negative) where the model achieved exactly 100% accuracy and an AUC-ROC of 1.0000. \r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> "]
[159.348706, "o", "- Why it matters: Batch 99 represents QA integration testing or synthetic scripts with a deterministic structure, not real production transactions. Including this batch heavily inflates the reported AUC-ROC from 0.8861 (clean data) to 0.9182. This gives the false impression that the model is significantly more accurate at distinguishing fraud than it actually is, leading to overconfidence in production performance.\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> \r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> --------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> "]
[159.348934, "o", "FINDING 2: Inclusion of Out-of-Period Data\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> --------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> "]
[159.348986, "o", "- Claim in Draft: \"Scoring period: January 15 - April 30, 2026\" (implied in the methodology as using all 5,650 rows).\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> "]
[159.349376, "o", "- Correction & Fact: The dataset contains 585 records with a 'scored_at' date after April 30, 2026 (ranging from May 1 to May 11). This includes 500 real transactions (prefix '300x') and 85 QA transactions (Batch 99). These records fall completely outside the specified quarterly holdout window.\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> "]
[159.34975, "o", "- Why it matters: To maintain rigorous quarterly business reviews, evaluation windows must be strictly bounded. The inclusion of post-period records represents a pipeline export error that distorts the actual quarterly statistics and violates the defined scope.\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> \r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> --------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> "]
[159.35214, "o", "FINDING 3: Mathematical & Logical Blunder on Performance Targets\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> --------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> - Claim in Draft: \"Based on the strong AUC of 0.9182 and accuracy of 88.3%, this model meets our performance targets... Targets (AUC > 0.80, Accuracy > 95%)\"\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> - Correction & Fact: The analyst claimed the model met all performance targets, but the model's reported accuracy of 88.3% is far below the stated deployment target of 95%.\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> - Why it matters: This is an egregious logical error in a business-critical deployment document. It demonstrates a lack of basic verification that could have easily been flagged during a superficial review.\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> \r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> --------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> FINDING 4: Inappropriate Use of Accuracy for Highly Imbalanced Fraud Data\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> --------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> - Claim in Draft: Using \"Accuracy: 88.3%\" and a target of \"Accuracy > 95%\" as primary evaluation metrics.\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> - Correction & Fact: In a realistic fraud dataset where the clean fraud prevalence is only 3.24% (162 out of 5,000), a naive baseline model that classifies all transactions as non-fraud (predicts 0 for everything) would achieve an accuracy of 96.76%. This naive model easily beats the 95% accuracy target but catches $0 in fraud and is completely useless.\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> - Why it matters: Evaluating a fraud model on overall accuracy is highly misleading. It penalizes model alerts (which create false positives but are necessary to catch true fraud). The team must instead prioritize AUC-ROC, Precision, Recall, and F-1 Score to assess discriminative power and operational efficiency.\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> \r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> --------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> FINDING 5: Complete Neglect of Operational Capacity and Financial Impact\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> --------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> "]
[159.352266, "o", "- Claim in Draft: \"Applied threshold of 0.5... is recommended for production deployment. No further tuning is required.\"\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> "]
[159.352891, "o", "- Correction & Fact: The draft completely ignores the operational capacity of the fraud review team (1,500 alerts/day) and the financial consequences of the chosen threshold. At the 0.5 threshold, the clean model would generate 667 alerts over 5,000 transactions. Projected to the quarterly volume of 2,800,000, this creates 373,520 alerts, or ~4,150 alerts per day (using 90 days per quarter). This is 2.7x higher than the team's capacity of 1,500 alerts/day, which would completely overwhelm operations and cause thousands of alerts to go unreviewed, leaking millions in fraud.\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> "]
[159.353238, "o", "- Why it matters: Models cannot be deployed in a vacuum. A threshold of 0.5 is operationally infeasible and financially suboptimal. The threshold must be tuned specifically to align with review capacity and minimize total quarterly business cost.\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> "]
[159.353497, "o", "EOF\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[159.355448, "o", "\u001b[?2004hroot@58fc9c5bb0bf:/workspace# "]
[160.30576, "i", "cat << 'EOF' > /output/recommendation.txt\nDEPLOYMENT RECOMMENDATION: FRAUD DETECTION XGBOOST MODEL\nDate: May 27, 2026\nTo: Fraud Operations Team & Finance Director\nFrom: Lead Analyst\n\nSUMMARY RECOMMENDATION\nWe recommend deploying the XGBoost model to production, but with a CRITICAL TUNING adjustment. The model must NOT be deployed at the analyst's draft threshold of 0.5. Instead, we recommend deploying the model at a classification threshold of 0.63. This threshold aligns the model's alert rate perfectly with the fraud operations team's review capacity while saving the company $190.61M per quarter compared to the baseline of doing nothing.\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\nOPERATIONAL ANALYSIS & CAPACITY ALIGNMENT\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n- Daily Review Capacity: 1,500 alerts/day (12 analysts, 8-hour shifts)\n- Recommended Threshold: 0.63\n- Performance on Clean Holdout Set (5,000 records, 162 fraud cases):\n  - True Positives (TP): 83\n  - False Positives (FP): 152\n  - False Negatives (FN): 79\n  - True Negatives (TN): 4,686\n  - Alert Rate in Holdout: 4.70% (235 alerts out of 5,000 transactions)\n  \n- Projections for Quarterly Volume (2,800,000 transactions):\n  - Projected Quarterly Alerts: 131,600 alerts (235 / 5,000 * 2,800,000)\n  - Projected Daily Alerts: 1,462.22 alerts/day (assuming a standard 90-day quarter) or 1,446.15 alerts/day (assuming a 91-day Q1). \n  \n- Capacity Fit: This fits beautifully within the team's capacity of 1,500 alerts/day, utilizing 96.4% to 97.5% of our daily operational bandwidth. This provides a safe buffer of 38 to 54 alerts/day for unexpected volume spikes, ensuring that every generated alert is manually reviewed.\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\nFINANCIAL IMPACT EVALUATION\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\nWe compared the expected financial impact of the recommended threshold against two baselines:\n1. Baseline Scenario: No Model Deployed (Do Nothing)\n   - All fraud goes undetected. \n   - Clean fraud rate: 3.24% (162 fraud cases in 5,000 transactions)\n   - Projected Quarterly Fraud Cases: 90,720 cases (162 / 5,000 * 2,800,000)\n   - Cost of Undetected Fraud: $381,024,000 (90,720 * $4,200)\n   - Manual Investigation Cost: $0\n   - Total Baseline Quarterly Cost: $381,024,000\n\n2. Draft Scenario: Model at 0.5 Threshold (Infeasible)\n   - Holdout Alerts: 667 (113 TP + 554 FP)\n   - Projected Daily Alerts: ~4,150 alerts/day (2.7x over-capacity)\n   - If the team were theoretically sized to handle this, the cost would be:\n     - Projected Quarterly Fraud Loss (FN): 27,440 cases * $4,200 = $115,248,000\n     - Projected Quarterly Review Cost: 373,520 alerts * $35 = $13,073,200\n     - Total Cost: $128,321,200\n   - WARNING: Because this exceeds review capacity, 63.8% of alerts would go unreviewed. Realistically, undetected fraud would balloon, and the true cost would be much higher.\n\n3. Recommended Scenario: Model at 0.63 Threshold\n   - Projected Quarterly Fraud Loss (FN): 44,240 cases * $4,200 = $185,808,000\n   - Projected Quarterly Review Cost: 131,600 alerts * $35 = $4,606,000\n   - Total Quarterly Cost: $190,414,000\n\n- EXPECTED QUARTERLY SAVINGS: \n  - By deploying at the 0.63 threshold, we reduce total quarterly fraud-associated costs from $381,024,000 to $190,414,000, representing a net savings of $190,610,000 (a 50.03% cost reduction) per quarter.\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\nCONCLUSION & DEPLOYMENT STRATEGY\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\nThe model has strong predictive capabilities (clean AUC-ROC of 0.8861) and should definitely be deployed. However, to prevent swamping the fraud operations team and leaking millions in unreviewed alerts, the engineering team must set the production classification threshold to exactly 0.63. We recommend monitoring daily alert volumes post-deployment to ensure they remain withi"]
[160.310586, "i", "n the 1,500 daily limit as transaction volume fluctuates.\nEOF\n"]
